EventItemTitle: A Local Law to amend the administrative code of the city of New York, in relation to city-wide ambient noise level monitoring.

EventItemTitle: A Local Law to amend the administrative code of the city of New York, in relation to fees for the installation of solar power energy systems.
EventItemMatterName: Fees for the installation of solar power energy systems.

EventItemActionText: This Resolution was Referred to Comm by Council to the Committee on Fire and Criminal Justice Services
EventItemTitle: Resolution calling on the federal government to continue Medicaid coverage for individuals while they are incarcerated in correctional facilities, including New York City jails.
EventItemMatterName: Continue Medicaid coverage for individuals while they are incarcerated in correctional facilities, including NYC jails.

EventItemTitle: A Local Law to amend the administrative code of the city of New York, in relation to strengthening the licensing requirements in the sight-seeing bus industry.
EventItemMatterName: Strengthening the licensing requirements in the sight-seeing bus industry.

EventItemTitle: A Local Law to amend the administrative code of the city of New York, in relation to authorizing an increase in the amount to be expended annually in ten business improvement districts.

EventItemActionText: This Resolution was Referred to Comm by Council to the Committee on Finance
EventItemTitle: Resolution concerning the increase in the annual expenditure for the Steinway Street, 34th Street, 125th Street, 47th Street, 86th Street Bay Ridge, Columbus/Amsterdam, Forest Avenue, Myrtle Avenue Brooklyn, 161st Street, and Sunnyside Business Improvement Districts, and the setting of the date, time and place for the hearing of the local law increasing the annual expenditure for such districts.

EventItemMatterName: Authorize the issuance of “Cure Childhood Cancer” license plates. (S.1485/A.1683)

EventItemMatterName: Allowing states and localities to grant disabled veterans access to high-occupancy vehicle lanes without risking the loss of federal highway funds.
